##The folk relay of Chinese cabbage

Micro-signal. NBWEEKLY

Introduction of function, new media with temperature

Huang Wei said that this kind of folk relay channel efficiency is the highest, also does not need the second transfer, "(vegetable) in the morning, in the afternoon sent directly, in the evening on the table. "

By Xie Chan, editor | Roo

There's been a lot of talk about the Coleslaw. Chen Weijia, who lives in Wuhan, wants to check the Internet to see if anyone has received a donated care dish.

He saw a variety of voices, some said his community has received three times the care of vegetables, others said he had never seen. Query is mixed in with the speech of thanks, the Internet can not find the open and comprehensive information, netizens do not know those tons as a unit of love dishes, whether they were really sent to the shelter hospital they cared about most, the designated hospital, the hotel where the medical staff lived, and the dining table of millions of ordinary people.

One Netizen said that after his parents were diagnosed, he received mutton and vegetables from the community, saying he "seemed to see hope. ". Chen Weijia thought, Wuhan is so big, the situation is different in all places, and in fact, there are not many heart-shaped vegetables. If you can really get them, it will probably be just a lettuce and a lettuce, but he is still full of expectations, "Hope that their community can also turn a radish. ".

The last mile of the Coleslaw

The Van Long Yun found is parked near the Wembley Arena. It was a huge truck nearly 20 meters long, carrying 30 tons of turnips from Sichuan. Since the outbreak, Long Yun has used his media contacts to reach out to vegetable donors in Yunnan, Sichuan, Guizhou and elsewhere, helping them send their vegetables to Wuhan, where they can be streamed live.

Long Yun will be broadcasting live as the cabbage is handed out.

Volunteer Huang Wei, a former peacekeeper who works for an advertising agency, coordinates the distribution of vegetables on the spot.

There were sixty cars parked in front of him, from every street, community, property committee. From him to collect donated vegetables.

Vegetables arrive in Wuhan, but reaching the People's table is not an easy task.

Huang Wei has worked with many community workers. The distribution of vegetables is an extremely labor-intensive process, and given the amount of work that most community workers can afford at present, "The supply-demand relationship of transport capacity is absolutely very unreasonable and can not be balanced. ".

In this folk relay, the rest of his life and his friends took the initiative to come forward as community volunteers. They have distributed more than 30,000 catties of heart-warming vegetables to the residents of the community.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Retweeting pictures of Mianyang Volunteers Picking turnips for the rest of their lives.

For a long time after the city was shut down, the focus of the epidemic prevention war was on medical issues. Patients infected with the new coronavirus struggled for beds, and for the rest of their lives, they watched as community workers "suddenly became on the line" to complete the screening, it's crazy busy transporting patients to the hospital.

The rest of my life I want to pay attention to the old people living alone and the five-guarantee families in my community, and I want to deliver food for them. But he also knows that community workers don't have the energy to take care of the small stuff.

The first batch of 5,000 Jin of food he found for the rest of his life was from other volunteers who coordinated the distribution. He did not know at the time which province the food came from.

The help the community was able to give him was a stamped certificate and a list of the elderly who lived alone in the community, and it was up to him and his friends to deal with the manpower, transport vehicles and protective gear.

But I was lucky enough to find 5,000 kilos. Huang Wei said, currently coordinated distribution of vegetables, the average community can only receive 500 Jin to 2,000 Jin Range.

For the rest of my life, I lived in a community, a community with a much larger population, and I started out with a little bit more vegetables, but lately I've only been able to get 1,000 Jin or 2,000 Jin. If is the radish this kind of comparison pressure scale's dish, according to each person 5 catties divides down, the old people can get only two turnips.

He once found 1000 pounds of Pomelo, originally want to drag back the next day to share food, but just in time to change the pass, all cars can not go out, they fear rotten Pomelo, can only quickly share. He felt that it was not worth going out for a couple of pomelos, that the elderly were a vulnerable group, and that every time he opened the door he took a great risk.

That list of old people living alone isn't accurate either. For the first time in the rest of their lives, many old people came downstairs to ask if they could take some vegetables home, but they were not on the list.

Only later in life did it become clear that the community's list counted only the elderly who were registered there. He and his friends added names to the list as they met new old people who lived alone.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For the rest of their lives, a team of volunteers handed out heart-warming vegetables to an unmanaged community. (photo provided by interviewees)

Tons is a huge-sounding unit. Huang Wei has seen truckloads of "30 tons" of vegetables enter Wuhan, but he says it's only a drop in the bucket. Only a small bag of vegetables ends up in the hands of residents, it might contain a cabbage and two or three potatoes, which the old man could eat for a day or two.

The owner of Tingtao community, which once lost the way to buy vegetables, has questioned the problem of never receiving heart-warming vegetables. From time to time, news of the distribution of heart-warming vegetables from several communities around -- sometimes Chinese cabbage, sometimes eggplant -- has been received, sometimes there's fruit. Residents of the Tingtao community can only envy the residents of other communities to see them in the wechat group to express gratitude.

In this regard, listen to Tao Community Secretary said, love is the streets to the community, the street population is too much, often love dishes down, to listen to Tao community here, the number is not much. They have no choice but to give priority to the elderly.

"This is the most efficient channel for the private sector. "

This is the most typical of the relay: Truck Drivers Transport donated vegetables to the outskirts of Wuhan, or to a temporary unloading warehouse, and local volunteers in Wuhan send out messages in advance, the community worker will pick it up with a community acceptance letter and distribute it to the residents.

Huang Wei said that such private relay channel efficiency is the highest, also does not need the second trans-shipment, "(vegetable) in the morning to the afternoon directly sent out, the evening on the table. "

As a temporary civilian volunteer, Huang could not say how many donated vegetables had entered Wuhan and where they had gone in the past month or so. He wasn't able to do all the statistical work. He could only make sure that every load of caring vegetables he handled was taken away by the communities in need, and that he kept all the community acceptance letters and thank you notes.

Each time before the dish, he is in Wechat ahead of the people who come to pick up the dish said, "first come, first served. ". It took less than an hour and a half to distribute the 30 tons of turnips that this car had brought from Sichuan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A truckload of 30 tons of white turnips donated by Sichuan was distributed in an hour and a half. (photo provided by interviewees)

Most of the volunteers from the beginning of the city began to participate in volunteer activities, has been more than a month, and gradually some powerless.

"My wife won't even give me money for gas now, " Huang said, half-jokingly. For the rest of his life, he and his team began making raincoats into protective suits.

The non-medical suits they found cost $110 each, but now they're a little hard to wear. It takes at least four or five volunteers to haul in food, which adds up to thousands of dollars in protective equipment and fuel costs. They're keeping track of every fare and gas, some of which are still outstanding. Whether or not these futures are covered, the rest of my life, I say, will have to be filled in by drivers sooner or later.

A steady stream of donors approached Long Yun, but the companies that had been in charge of making the initial donation gradually withdrew, leaving them short of funds for transportation. In Yunnan, for example, drivers pay about 13,000 yuan for a trip from Yunnan to Wuhan, Long Yun said. There's another 14 days of isolation back home, so there are fewer and fewer drivers.

In addition, the vehicle passes changed again, the road was artificially blocked, the driver can not go out of the city after delivering food... are the troubles they have faced. When the road is not easy to walk, Huang Wei said bluntly, "all kinds of bulldozing breaks make you doubt your life. " These volunteers are very hopeful that every trip will go smoothly, at least a little less man-made resistance.

In the early days, volunteers were almost always working on the front lines, and Huang Wei had transported medical staff, delivered supplies to the hospital and supported the Vulcan Mountain Hospital. For the rest of their lives, they worked at the mayor's hotline before delivering vegetables to the elderly and delivered protective supplies to hospitals, but then they all decided to jump into "another void" and help donate vegetables to families.

A media interview for the rest of his life, asked why insist on delivering food to the elderly. He could not answer for a moment, and asked the other brothers in the group. Some said, "for no regrets. ". He said, "yes, to no regrets. ".

A volunteer watched his companions unload a load of vegetables in the middle of the night and lamented in the circle of friends, "A lot of times, civilian volunteer teams have become 'black under the lamp, ' with no supplies or meals, and some are just enthusiastic. Wuhan has its present situation, not because of a refueling. "

Donated Vegetables "mostly come to the people. "

"Most [ of the donated vegetables ] have come to the people, " several volunteers told nandu weekly.

Another source of donations, Huang said, is through the district government, which distributes vegetables to public institutions or streets, with a letter of acceptance from the actual recipient.

Earlier, Long Yun had made a habit of linking up with district governments or district epidemic prevention headquarters, but each time he negotiated with the other in advance and had to hand out vegetables in person, live on the air. He knows what the public is most concerned about, but also most worried about, "the people have spent so much time and effort to grow vegetables, organized so much human and material resources to pull you over, the most concerned is where the vegetables end up. "

According to the division of responsibilities for the prevention and control of the Wuhan epidemic, vegetables donated from other places in Wuhan will be sold mainly by Wu Shang, Zhong Shang and Zhong Bai Shang, according to a statement issued by the Wuhan Municipal Bureau of Commerce on January 30, the sales revenue shall be turned over to the municipal finance, which shall be allocated as epidemic prevention funds.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At a press conference on February 29 on the prevention and control of COVID-19 pneumonia in Hubei Province, Xu Honglan, the vice mayor of Wuhan, said he would spare no effort to do a good job of covering up the bottom of the needy, wuhan offers 10 catties and 10 yuan vegetable bags to low-income groups. Other provinces and cities donate vegetables and materials to Wuhan and give priority to the needy.

On March 2, Nando weekly reported on the website of the Charity Federation of Wuhan that the announcement of the receipt and subsequent distribution and use of the materials had been updated to No. 3. Food donations are mainly targeted donations, and the recipients are public institutions such as hospitals or welfare institutions, district commerce bureau, District Emergency Management Bureau and other departments.

I hope more people pay attention to "common people's table" in Wuhan

At present, more than volunteers in the interview appeal, hope the public give Wuhan "common people dining table" more attention. During the day, Huang's phone has never been unplugged from the charger. It has been hot all day. At most, he can receive 321 calls a day, "all to beg for food. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Huang Wei's phone records.

Huang Wei said that although the public is generally concerned about whether the food supply in designated hospitals and hotels where medical staff live is normal, he understands that the governments of these units will ensure that the food supply is adequate, he tried to illustrate the point with a simple logic: "if a doctor delivers food for free, if you deliver it today and don't deliver it tomorrow, doesn't the doctor have anything to eat? "

Chen Weijia's family got the cabbage on February 26, more than he expected, and it looked like 10 Jin. The family members joked that they had rubbed their noses in GRANDPA's light. They inquired, the next door grandma and upstairs a lack of self-care ability aunt also received the care of vegetables. Everyone's happy.

He knew the dishes would soon be gone, but he was sure that they had dispelled the sense of crisis and anxiety that kept Wuhan people at home.

(Liu Tian contributed research.)
